  urldate = {2026-06-28},
  abstract = {Fusion categories offer a systematic framework for constructing quantum lattice models with non-invertible symmetries and dualities. This thesis examines the quantum phases and transitions realized in a specific 1+1d lattice model and develops these ideas further to study 2+1d models with topological order. {$<$}br{$>$}After a brief review of fusion categories, anyon chains, and string-nets in Chapter 2, Chapter 3 investigates a model of Rydberg-blockade atoms on the square ladder with at most one excited atom per square. Along an integrable line, it is equivalent to the 1+1d anyon chain built from the {$<$}em{$>$}so{$<$}/em{$>$}(3)\textsubscript{2} fusion category and preserves a non-invertible self-duality symmetry that can be spontaneously broken. A duality mapping to the spin-1/2 XXZ chain reveals a critical line governed by the free boson orbifold CFT. A non-invertible remnant of the XXZ chain's {$<$}em{$>$}U(1){$<$}/em{$>$} symmetry applies to the full three-parameter space of couplings and distinguishes two different Z\textsubscript{3} ordered phases. Away from integrability, we use perturbation theory and DMRG to explore a rich phase diagram with several density-wave phases separated by critical and first-order transitions. {$<$}br{$>$}The second part of this thesis focuses on 2+1d fusion surface models, higher-dimensional extensions of anyon chains built from braided fusion categories. In Chapter 4, we develop systematic generalizations of Kitaev’s honeycomb model, which itself can be formulated as a fusion surface model built from the Ising category. These models exhibit categorical 1-form symmetries and have phase diagrams qualitatively similar to Kitaev’s, including a weakly coupled chains phase capable of hosting chiral topological order, as demonstrated in a Z\textsubscript{3} symmetric example. Chapter 5 shows that dualities between such models arise by refining the input data with module tensor categories, paralleling the construction of dual 1+1d anyon chains. The resulting 2+1d models support both 0-form and 1-form symmetries and are candidates for realizing symmetry-enriched topological phases. Taken together, these results point towards a broader framework for 2+1d quantum lattice models beyond commuting projectors, with Chapter 6 outlining connections to 3d criticality, quantum scars, and quantum error correction.},
  langid = {english},
  annotation = {ark:/29072/ora\_bcb39a311eaa403dbcf8c7be6fb3d4d8},
  file = {/home/jkr/Zotero/storage/ZIWL6H37/Eck - 2025 - Quantum lattice models from fusion categories.pdf}
}

